<text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
  <body>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="MuTA33">
<l>pālakaṉā yālilaimēṟ paiya vulakellā</l>
<l>mēlorunā ḷuṇṭavaṉē meymmaiyē – mālavaṉē</l>
<l>mantarattāṉ mānīrk kaṭalkaṭaintu vāṉamuta</l>
<l>mantarattārk kīntāynī yaṉṟu</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>O you who, as a boy on a banyan leaf, gently ate</l>
<l>all the worlds on a former day, truly<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">meymmaiyē can either be taken as an adverb or as another vocative “o [you] truth”.</note>, infatuating<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">mālavaṉ appears only here in the early Antāti-s and can either be seen as an extension of the proper noun Māl or as pronominal derivation from māl in one of its three meanings: “delusion”, “darkness”, “greatness”.</note> one,</l> 
<l>that day you churned the sea of dark waters with the Mandara mountain</l>
<l>[and] gave the heavenly ambrosia to them of the intermediate space.</l>
      </lg>
    </div>
